\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

We have presented Token-Context Semantic Grammar (TSCG), a formal framework for deterministic prompt optimization in large language models. TSCG comprises eight principles---TAS, CFL, CFO, SDM, DRO, CCP, CAS, and SAD-F---each grounded in a specific property of causal autoregressive transformer processing: BPE tokenization alignment, the attention sink phenomenon, causal attention directionality, and recency bias in generation.

Our theoretical analysis establishes formal connections between these principles and transformer attention mechanics, introducing the fragility score as a novel metric for quantifying parameter criticality under causal attention, and proving that semantic density maximization improves effective attention per semantic atom (Proposition 1).

Empirically, TSCG achieves up to 100\% accuracy on a 19-task core benchmark across seven categories---the only strategy to achieve perfect accuracy in any run---while achieving consistent token savings of 6.3\% compared to natural language baselines. Extended evaluation across 25 hard tests and 82 domain-specific tests (long-context retrieval, RAG, and tool use) reveals that TSCG's token savings scale dramatically with domain structure, reaching 71.7\% on tool-description optimization. The v1.1.0 clean domain evaluation, free of the rate-limiting confounds that affected earlier results, yields the first statistically significant accuracy improvement: TSCG improves long-context needle-in-a-haystack retrieval from 50.0\% to 83.3\% (McNemar $p = 0.0063$), validating the theoretical prediction that attention-density compression increases the signal-to-noise ratio in long-context retrieval.

A controlled comparison with LLMLingua-2~\cite{pan2024llmlingua2} on 30 tool-use tests demonstrates that TSCG is strictly superior to statistical token pruning on structured content: 90.6\% token savings at 93.3\% accuracy versus LLMLingua-2's 60.6\% savings at 80.0\% accuracy. The compound pipeline (TSCG then LLMLingua-2) yields 0\% accuracy, revealing that TSCG already removes all structural redundancy---no safe tokens remain for statistical pruning. This establishes that structural and statistical compression target fundamentally different redundancy types and are not composable on structured content.

Multi-model evaluation across four models reveals a nuanced transferability landscape. Claude Sonnet 4 benefits most (TSCG 95.5\% vs.\ Natural 93.2\% combined accuracy). GPT-5.2 achieves 100\% Tool Use accuracy across all strategies, 73.9\% token savings, and improved RAG accuracy under TSCG (95.5\% vs.\ 90.9\% Natural), establishing it as the most TSCG-compatible non-Anthropic model. GPT-4o and Gemini 2.5 Flash show partial incompatibility: both echo CFL format annotations (e.g., \texttt{[ANSWER:type]}) rather than treating them as meta-instructions, leading to significant TSCG+SAD degradation ($p=0.0391$ and $p=0.0117$ respectively). However, Gemini 2.5 Flash exhibits a notable \emph{positive} interaction on Tool Use where TSCG outperforms Natural (90.0\% vs.\ 83.3\%). To address the CFL echo-back problem, we introduce model-adaptive CFL profiles (v1.2.0) that selectively disable format annotations for incompatible models while preserving benefits on Claude and GPT-5.2.

The implementation---approximately 1,200 lines of TypeScript with zero external dependencies, producing a 27.7\,KB browser bundle---demonstrates that formally grounded prompt optimization can be practical, portable, and efficient. The v1.1.0 infrastructure additions (provider abstraction for four LLM providers, rate limiter with token budget tracking, 435 total tests) further demonstrate production readiness. The three deployment modes (CLI, browser extension, web application) provide accessibility across development workflows.

To our knowledge, TSCG is the first prompt optimization framework that unifies tokenizer awareness, budgeted anchoring, causal attention theory, deterministic transforms, and black-box compatibility within a single formal system. We hope that TSCG's principled approach---treating prompt optimization as a well-defined engineering discipline rather than an ad hoc art---contributes to more reliable, efficient, and reproducible use of large language models.
